\end{align*} Since Williams has outperformed the benchmark for 6 months in a row, $h=6$, and we don't know how much $y$ will be, but we do know that the total number of months is $y+h=12$. Using the formula, we conclude that: \begin{align*} P(\text{Williams outperforms benchmark annually}) = \tfrac{6}{12+6} = \tfrac{6}{18} = \boxed{\tfrac{6}{9}}
